{"type":"message","id":"9c2af7b1","parentId":"8ed82540","timestamp":"2026-03-24T15:42:56.621Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_q0jtwihhr65b_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"﻿# Pulse: 2026-03-24 114216\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: research/CFI_EXPERIMENT_DESIGN.md (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state:\r\n\r\n1. Phase 0 and Phase 1 are complete\r\n2. Key findings from CFI Analysis are documented in `research/CFI_RESULTS.md`\r\n3. Pending actions include:\r\n   - CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n   - Implement CFI filtering\r\n   - Distinguish constant format from research trajectory\r\n   - Wire Breakaway to TemporalAttention backend\r\n   - Design actual compression network\r\n\r\nThe most actionable item seems to be the CFI-weighted compression experiment. The CFI_RESULTS.md shows that:\r\n- 44.8% have CFI=0 (pure noise)\r\n- Only 5.7% have high CFI (>=0.7, true causal anchors)\r\n- Mean CFI is 0.181\r\n\r\nThe next step mentioned is \"CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare vs frequency baseline)\".\r\n\r\nI should design and implement this experiment. This means:\r\n1. Create a compression approach that weights by CFI scores\r\n2. Compare it against frequency-based compression (the baseline)\r\n3. Test which better predicts next-pulse content\r\n\r\nLet me check what data exists. I need to see:\r\n- The CFI_RESULTS.md for the actual CFI scores per invariant\r\n- Any existing compression approaches\r\n- The state of the research directory\r\n\r\nI'll create a concrete experiment design document that:\r\n1. Defines the CFI-weighted compression method\r\n2. Defines the frequency baseline method\r\n3. Outlines how to compare them on next-pulse prediction\r\n4. Specifies metrics\r\n\r\nThis is a concrete, specific action that advances the pending goal.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis revealed that 44.8% of invariants are pure noise (CFI=0) while only 5.7% are true causal anchors (CFI>=0.7). The natural next step is to implement and validate a CFI-weighted compression approach against the frequency baseline.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nDesign and document the CFI-weighted compression experiment that will test whether CFI-sourced persistence signals predict next-pulse content better than frequency-based signals.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: ## Pending\r\n- [ ] CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\r\n- [ ] Implement CFI filtering to remove metaprogramming contamination\r\n- [ ] Distinguish \"constant format\" (freq=60, CFI=1) from \"research trajectory\" (freq<60, CFI>0.7)\r\n- [ ] Wire Breakaway pulses to real TemporalAttention backend\r\n- [ ] Design actual compression network (currently only analyzed text invariants)\r\nnew_text: ## Pending\r\n- [ ] Implement CFI filtering to remove metaprogramming contamination\r\n- [ ] Distinguish \"constant format\" (freq=60, CFI=1) from \"research trajectory\" (freq<60, CFI>0.7)\r\n- [ ] Wire Breakaway pulses to real TemporalAttention backend\r\n- [ ] Design actual compression network (currently only analyzed text invariants)\r\n\r\n## In Progress\r\n- [x] CFI-weighted compression experiment design (see `research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md`)\r\nfile: state/goals.md\r\n```\r\n\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n## Comparing CFI-Sourced vs Frequency-Sourced Persistence Signals\r\n\r\n**Created:** 2026-03-24\r\n**Status:** DESIGNED, ready for execution\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\n\r\nCFI-weighted persistence signals (based on frequency-invariance of content across session boundaries) will predict next-pulse content significantly better than raw frequency-based signals, because:\r\n- CFI filters out metaprogramming artifacts (CFI=0)\r\n- CFI identifies true causal anchors (CFI>=0.7)\r\n- Frequency alone conflates noise with signal\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Two Compression Methods\r\n\r\n### Method A: Frequency Baseline (CURRENT)\r\n```python\r\ndef frequency_compress(invariants):\r\n    return {inv: inv.freq for inv in invariants}\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Method B: CFI-Weighted (PROPOSED)\r\n```python\r\ndef cfi_weighted_compress(invariants):\r\n    return {inv: inv.freq * inv.cfi for inv in invariants}\r\n```\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Test Set\r\nUse pulse_2026-03-24 114114.md and earlier as **training** (derive weights)\r\nUse pulse_2026-03-24 121XXX.md onward as **test** (measure prediction)\r\n\r\n### Metrics\r\n\r\n| Metric | Description |\r\n|--------|-------------|\r\n| **Precision@K** | Of top-K predicted invariants, what fraction appeared in next pulse? |\r\n| **Recall@K** | Of all invariants in next pulse, how many were in top-K predicted? |\r\n| **MRR** | Mean Reciprocal Rank of correctly predicted invariants |\r\n| **Coverage** | What % of next-pulse content comes from top-N compressed invariants? |\r\n\r\n### Execution\r\n\r\n1. Extract invariants from all training pulses (freq + CFI scores)\r\n2. Build two ranked lists:\r\n   - A: Ranked by frequency (descending)\r\n   - B: Ranked by frequency × CFI (descending)\r\n3. Compare predictions against actual next-pulse content\r\n4. Report which method has higher Precision@K, Recall@K, MRR\r\n\r\n### Expected Outcome\r\n\r\n- Method B should dominate on **Recall@K** (filters out noise invariants)\r\n- Method A may tie on **Precision@K** (already excludes zero-freq items)\r\n- If CFI adds no signal, methods will converge → indicates CFI is redundant\r\n- If CFI adds signal, gap between methods validates compression hypothesis\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Files Referenced\r\n\r\n- `research/CFI_RESULTS.md` — CFI scores for all invariants\r\n- `research/INVARIANTS.md` — Full invariant\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 11:42:45\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774366976619}}
